{"$ambrosia":"aero:interactive:9417ac60-5f60-11ea-8e69-affb2224d7e8:*","$id":"09be4160-44e0-11ed-8212-a06d21a99e09","$workspaceId":"7fff47c0-44d6-11ed-bcef-d5307f42495c","$projectId":"86cb0040-44df-11ed-8442-dbcbc27803ca","annotations":[],"configSchemaVersion":"/pluginGenericSchema/v1","config":{"stage":{"sections":[{"rowsAreFullWidth":false,"backgroundImageUrl":"","rows":[{"columns":[{"stageElements":[{"type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"heading-two","ref":"dfd01491-62f7-4243-b8b4-53cd883f7fd7","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Optimal Capital Structure: The Tradeoff Theory","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]}},"config":{"cssClass":""},"ref":"8eca6968-fa61-406a-b8b3-645123bbf657"}]}]},{"columns":[{"stageElements":[{"type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"ordered-list","data":{"listOptionType":"1","startValue":26},"ref":"002bc558-313d-4b92-ac9c-9cdf285c8b2e","nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"list-item","data":{"direction":"auto"},"ref":"1804e591-6f4e-4fba-99df-4e3bf61f16ef","nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"d2c03361-0e23-4186-ac35-059280a683e8","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"With its current leverage, Impi Corporation will have net income next year of $4.5 million. If Impi’s corporate tax rate is 21% and it pays 8% interest on its debt, how much additional debt can Impi issue this year and still receive the benefit of the interest tax shield next year?","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]},{"object":"block","type":"list-item","data":{"direction":"auto"},"ref":"98f90ca2-e37f-495d-b127-e24aafe3901f","nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"569c33c0-8e78-41a4-b8c8-b61eacbe1b62","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Now that your firm has matured, you are considering adding debt to your capital structure for the first time. Your all-equity firm has a market value of $20 million and you are considering issuing $2 million in debt with an interest rate of 7% and using it to repurchase shares. You pay a corporate tax rate of 25%. Assume taxes are the only imperfection and the debt is expected to be permanent.","marks":[]}],"data":{}},{"object":"block","type":"ordered-list","data":{"listOptionType":"a","startValue":1},"ref":"98874ee0-6e1d-4f7d-a1f9-e3c3eb31f7b5","nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"list-item","data":{"direction":"auto"},"ref":"eeba544b-5f60-413e-b59e-17bdf9283162","nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"e181edb6-0bcc-43c6-b5b9-b98c4fcdbce1","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"What will be the total value of the firm after the change in capital structure?","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]},{"object":"block","type":"list-item","data":{"direction":"auto"},"ref":"aec326e1-fb47-42a2-853f-8771cc667f3f","nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"54601248-8561-4255-ba80-933e057afe08","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"What will be the value of the remaining equity after the change in capital structure?","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]}]}]},{"object":"block","type":"list-item","data":{"direction":"auto"},"ref":"33c07c90-002b-4580-afd1-4847acce7ad8","nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"a1a68f16-8fd4-4675-867a-acf31a18f279","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Hawar International is a shipping firm with a current share price of $5.50 and 10 million shares outstanding. Suppose that Hawar announces plans to lower its corporate taxes by borrowing $20 million and repurchasing shares, that Hawar pays a corporate tax rate of 20%, and that shareholders expect the change in debt to be permanent.","marks":[]}],"data":{}},{"object":"block","type":"ordered-list","data":{"listOptionType":"a","startValue":1},"ref":"3c91db15-4477-4205-a54a-f852b2445a03","nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"list-item","data":{"direction":"auto"},"ref":"3c17a36c-5839-473b-b692-d47092ac4432","nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"f2e699e5-c9e9-4cb6-acbc-579b26b49838","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"If the only imperfection is corporate taxes, what will the share price be after this announcement?","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]},{"object":"block","type":"list-item","data":{"direction":"auto"},"ref":"c064b623-d74f-4479-b2cc-4ce42ccc6bab","nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"54d23e59-2cb4-4c45-83da-e23664df8a84","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Suppose the only imperfections are corporate taxes and financial distress costs. If the share price rises to $5.75 after this announcement, what is the PV of financial distress costs Hawar will incur as the result of this new debt?","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]}]}]},{"object":"block","type":"list-item","data":{"direction":"auto"},"ref":"dae5fe33-3337-46a8-b0f9-24e444e58eaf","nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"9448ccd8-42c3-4e16-a6e7-68b98c2511ee","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Marpor Industries has no debt and expects to generate free cash flows of $16 million each year. Marpor believes that if it permanently increases its level of debt to $40 million, the risk of financial distress may cause it to lose some customers and receive less favorable terms from its suppliers. As a result, Marpor’s expected free cash flows with debt will be only $15 million per year. Suppose Marpor’s tax rate is 21%, the risk-free rate is 5%, the expected return of the market is 15%, and the beta of Marpor’s free cash flows is 1.10 (with or without leverage).","marks":[]}],"data":{}},{"object":"block","type":"ordered-list","data":{"listOptionType":"a","startValue":1},"ref":"bd16baf4-151c-41b5-b8a4-e74dfec1cc55","nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"list-item","data":{"direction":"auto"},"ref":"bdc660d6-d667-4afa-8a9f-f7e4d2c69bc4","nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"10af4777-198f-46f3-8bac-41fd9a1db6a5","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Estimate Marpor’s value without leverage.","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]},{"object":"block","type":"list-item","data":{"direction":"auto"},"ref":"014bbbc3-7d56-4256-bf9a-2b3850d1bbe0","nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"9d4dfc5b-b04b-4d1b-8575-38e2482ab10c","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Estimate Marpor’s value with the new leverage.","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]}]}]},{"object":"block","type":"list-item","data":{"direction":"auto"},"ref":"1e52239c-b3e1-4cb6-bce1-35a274929a0d","nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"977fa371-9207-40e5-b1be-d5c1343543c4","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Colt Systems will have EBIT this coming year of $15 million. It will also spend $6 million on total capital expenditures and increases in net working capital, and have $3 million in depreciation expenses. Colt is currently an all-equity firm with a corporate tax rate of 21% and a cost of capital of 10%.","marks":[]}],"data":{}},{"object":"block","type":"ordered-list","data":{"listOptionType":"a","startValue":1},"ref":"c513ed3a-504c-40db-a179-bd138cb3e705","nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"list-item","data":{"direction":"auto"},"ref":"61b0fac5-2219-472e-86ab-3ad5851a8d85","nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"ffd8d32f-6ef9-4e5a-8e34-781ea077ff92","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"If Colt’s free cash flows are expected to grow by 8.5% per year, what is the market value of its equity today?","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]},{"object":"block","type":"list-item","data":{"direction":"auto"},"ref":"44e2a7f1-06c1-4954-b620-e70610942fb0","nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"7368c559-90ae-467b-b255-1d706813b072","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"If the interest rate on its debt is 8%, how much can Colt borrow now and still have non-negative net income this coming year?","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]},{"object":"block","type":"list-item","data":{"direction":"auto"},"ref":"eca941b8-8714-47dc-b734-39f49578ca05","nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"8fd60f06-6b63-439a-8168-56e768293376","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Is there a tax incentive today for Colt to choose a debt-to-value ratio that exceeds 50%? Explain.","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]}]}]}]}]}},"config":{"cssClass":""},"ref":"54215149-254f-495e-a142-caeff618cf7c"}]}]}]}]},"screenType":"","transitions":{"enter":{"animation":"","duration":0,"easing":"","customKeyframes":""},"exit":{"animation":"","duration":0,"easing":"","customKeyframes":""}},"lockElements":false,"learnerCurrentAttempt":1,"footer":{"buttonText":"Next","buttonIcon":"Arrow","showFooter":false,"showHistoryNavButtons":false,"previewFooter":false,"position":"Fixed to screen bottom","footerComponent":{"showFooterDropArea":"hide","width":100,"footerComponentsAlignment":"right"}},"styles":{"background":{},"stage":{"maxWidth":940,"background":"rgba(255, 255, 255, 1)","responsive":true,"padding":{"vertical":60,"horizontal":60},"border":{"color":"rgba(224, 224, 224, 1)","radius":0,"width":0}},"elements":{"padding":{"vertical":10,"horizontal":10}},"footer":{"buttonColor":"rgba(0, 115, 202, 1)","textColor":"rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.7)","backgroundColor":"rgba(255, 255, 255, 1)","padding":10,"corners":4,"border":"none","shadow":"0 -1px 4px 0 rgba(0,0,0,0.06), 0 0 12px 2px rgba(0,0,0,0.1)"},"feedback":{"width":320,"textColor":"rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.7)","backgroundColor":"rgba(255, 255, 255, 1)","corners":4,"border":"none","shadow":"0 5px 47px 10px rgba(0,0,0,0.15), 0 10px 20px 2px rgba(0,0,0,0.1), 0 7px 8px 0 rgba(0,0,0,0.1)"}},"title":"Optimal Capital Structure: The Tradeoff Theory"},"assets":[],"scenarios":[],"pluginPayload":{"pluginRepositoryPath":"https://plugin-repository-bronte-qaint.pearson.com/9417ac60-5f60-11ea-8e69-affb2224d7e8/0.15.209/ac43ee4c0eda05e9718fa83a5aed4cff.zip","summary":{"pluginId":"9417ac60-5f60-11ea-8e69-affb2224d7e8","name":"Screen","description":"A screen of a lesson","type":"screen","latestVersion":"0.15.209","subscriptionId":"f0afd4d0-d2ff-11ea-9998-d57e1e28aca1","createdAt":"Fri, 6 Mar 2020 04:11:39 GMT","updatedAt":"Tue, 13 Dec 2022 22:07:46 GMT","tags":[],"publishMode":"DEFAULT"}},"activityThemeIconLibraries":[]}